definition: to put out the light or fire of
to cool (something, such as heated metal) suddenly by immersion (as in oil or water)
to cause to lose heat or warmth
examples: you have quenched the warmth of France toward you

definition: to bring (something immaterial) to an end typically by satisfying, damping, cooling, or decreasing
examples: a rational understanding of the laws of nature can quench impossible desires
the praise that quenches all desire to read the book

definition: to terminate by or as if by destroying : eliminate
examples: the Commonwealth party quenched a whole generation of play-acting

definition: to relieve or satisfy with liquid
examples: quenched his thirst at a wayside spring
